\subsection{Geometric Singularity and State-Space Topologies}
\label{subsec:gspt_topology}

We model the non-equilibrium transitions of the nocturnal stable boundary layer (SBL) as a constrained vector field on a four-dimensional differentiable manifold with boundary. Let $\mathcal{X}$ denote the state space:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{X}=\left\{\mathbf{x}=(e,U,V,T_s)^T\in\mathbb{R}_+\times\mathbb{R}\times\mathbb{R}\times\mathbb{R}_+\right\}\subset\mathbb{R}^4
\end{equation}
where $e$ represents the turbulent kinetic energy (TKE) density, $(U,V)$ denote the components of the horizontal velocity vector, and $T_s$ is the land surface skin temperature.

\paragraph{Time-Scale Separation.}
The system exhibits a natural time-scale separation governed by the singular perturbation parameter $\varepsilon$:
\begin{equation}
0<\varepsilon\ll1,\quad \varepsilon\coloneqq\frac{\tau_{\text{turb}}}{\tau_{\text{macro}}}
\end{equation}
Here $\tau_{\text{turb}}$ is the rapid turbulent relaxation timescale, typically $\mathcal{O}(10^1\,\text{s})$, while $\tau_{\text{macro}}$ is the slow synoptic-thermodynamic forcing timescale, typically $\mathcal{O}(10^3\text{--}10^4\,\text{s})$. This partition yields the fast-slow decomposition:
\begin{align}
\varepsilon\dot{e}&=\mathcal{F}(e,U,V,T_s) \\
\dot{\mathbf{y}}&=\mathbf{G}(e,\mathbf{y}),\quad \mathbf{y}\coloneqq(U,V,T_s)^T\in\mathbb{R}^3
\end{align}

\subsection{Critical Manifolds and Algebraic Regularization}

In the singular limit $\varepsilon\to0$, the fast-slow flow collapses onto the critical manifold $\mathcal{M}_0$, defined as the algebraic subvariety:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{M}_0\coloneqq\left\{\mathbf{x}\in\mathcal{X}\ \vert\ \mathcal{F}(e,U,V,T_s)=0\right\}
\end{equation}

\begin{theorem}[Active-Branch Geometry]
The unperturbed critical manifold $\mathcal{M}_0$ contains a single admissible active turbulent branch $\mathcal{M}_{\mathrm{act}}$ satisfying the explicit algebraic condition:
\begin{equation}
e^*=l_0\Delta-\delta,\quad \Delta\coloneqq\eta\,\gamma\,(U^2+V^2)-K\,G(T_s)
\end{equation}
with admissibility condition $e^*\ge0$, equivalently $\Delta\ge\delta/l_0$. Along this branch,
\begin{equation}
\partial_e\mathcal{F}\big|_{\mathcal{M}_{\mathrm{act}}}=-\sqrt{\Delta/l_0}<0\qquad (\Delta>0),
\end{equation}
so $\mathcal{M}_{\mathrm{act}}$ is normally hyperbolic and attracting away from the threshold. Because $e^*$ depends affinely on $\Delta$, the present closure does not generate an interior saddle-node fold; the regime transition occurs at the admissibility boundary $e^*=0$.
\end{theorem}

\paragraph{Elliptic Paraboloid Interpretation and Frictional Regularization.}
Geometrically, the state profile $\Delta(U,V;T_s)$ defines a circular elliptic paraboloid in the $(U,V,e)$ projection for any fixed thermodynamic state $T_s$. The principal curvatures of this manifold correspond directly to the eigenvalues ($\lambda_1,\lambda_2$) of the localized Hessian matrix:
\begin{equation}
H=\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{\partial^2\Delta}{\partial U^2} & \frac{\partial^2\Delta}{\partial U\partial V} \\
\frac{\partial^2\Delta}{\partial V\partial U} & \frac{\partial^2\Delta}{\partial V^2}
\end{pmatrix}
\end{equation}
The rotational symmetry of the mechanical production term ensures $\lambda_1=\lambda_2=2\eta\gamma$, forming circular cross-sections centered about the non-turbulent wind core.

This geometric framework also clarifies why the local quadratic-fit RMSE behaves oppositely from a naive “rougher means more complex” intuition. High-roughness environments such as FLOSS increase the drag coefficient $\gamma$, which acts as a strong dynamical damper. The trajectory is then rapidly pulled toward a tight local neighborhood in phase space, so a single quadratic patch provides a low global fit error.

By contrast, low-roughness environments such as CASES99 are weakly damped phase-space domains. When strong surface cooling drives $T_s \ll T_a$, the growth of $G(T_s)$ shifts the active branch downward in $e$ and expands the critical radius in the $(U,V)$ plane required to sustain turbulence, triggering a turbulence collapse toward the regularized background floor. As the active turbulence vanishes, the frictional drag components in Equations~\eqref{eq:slow_u} and \eqref{eq:slow_v} are suppressed:
\begin{equation}
\gamma\sqrt{e+\delta}\to\gamma\sqrt{\delta}\approx0
\end{equation}
Freed from turbulent friction, the slow momentum vector detaches from its steady-state balance and enters expansive clockwise Blackadar inertial circuits around the geostrophic vector $(U_g,V_g)$ at frequency $f$. These wide excursions sweep across more nonlinear regions of the manifold, so a single quadratic surface fit exhibits a larger geometric deviation. In this interpretation, the fit error measures unconstrained phase-space exploration rather than ambient observational noise.

\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{$C^\infty$}{C-infinity} Regularization.}
To prevent gradient discontinuities near the active-to-laminar transition, the reduced diagnostic branch can be regularized via a smooth hyperbolic embedding parameterized by $0<\xi\ll1$:
\begin{equation}
e^*_{\xi}=\frac{1}{2}\left(e^*+\sqrt{(e^*)^2+\xi^2}\right)
\end{equation}
This formulation ensures that the reduced closures for momentum and heat exchange, $K_{m,h}\propto\sqrt{e^*_{\xi}+\delta}$, remain strictly $C^\infty$ over the entire diagnostic domain. In the full ODE, the implemented solver adds a separate smooth floor gate to the fast tendency as $e\to-\delta$, so the state remains numerically forward-invariant while still transitioning smoothly between active shear-driven mixing and the residual laminar floor.
